metadata.name: Syzers #82
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

···· On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned ····

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

Click to listen to the sounds

Many thanks to @Jpupper and @Fipiaggio for help with programming the sound part and @Purespider for the template. 
"FXHASH PFP Token Generator" https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

for best resolution "open live" then use the "download image" button on the lower right corner ;)

metadata.name: Cuts #47
metadata.description:
Cuts is an abstract representation of the exact moments in our lives when something is cut. It could be moving to a different country, being fired, quitting a bad habit, when a relationship ends or when you receive a very bad (or good!) news.
By themselves, cuts are not positive or negative events; it really depends on who you were before and who you wish to be after. But one thing is sure: every cut creates a new space that wasn’t there. This space could be small or huge, ordered or chaotic, regardless, you have to deal with it. Sometimes cuts try to resist and heal themselves extruding the core of the fibres we are made of, but they will fail. A cut is irreversible and it’s up to us to fill the gap with meaning.

Main features include:
- Curated palettes (21)
- Drawing modes (3)
- Extrusions (yes/no)
- Orientation (3)
- Overlapping (yes/no)
- Covered area (2)
- Cut position (2)

In live mode:
- Press [s] to save a 2400x2400 px image
- Press [t] to toggle shading (sometimes flat colours rock!)
- Press [c] to see copyright notice
- Press [f] to log features in console

By Todemashi 2022
NFT License 2.0

### NOTES
Made with p5js and GLSL shaders.
Shaders are based on tutorials and code by Patricio Gonzalez Vivo - The Book of Shaders - https://thebookofshaders.com/

metadata.name: Disturbed #40
metadata.description:
Space-time has been Disturbed. The source of the disturbance is unknown. However, sensors now indicate the presence of a Demon Overlord in the sector. Your token gives you a snapshot of the space-time perturbations at your particular location-moment of space-time. 

Your token's unique hash determines its features:

- demon overlord
- inherent vice level
- probe size  
- orientation 
- sector location

Your token's output is dimension agnostic and scales seamlessly to any screen size.

metadata.name: fx_dungeon #26
metadata.description:
Welcome to the fx_dungeon. Every cartridge comes loaded with a random amount of levels between 2 (common) and 7 (rare). Your goal is to collect all the coins that are disseminated around the level. Each cartridge comes with the total amount of coins that can be collected displayed on the front. 

Token levels are generated from the transaction hash and are never the same between different tokens. Scattered around the levels are also some random amount of decorative props. There are different types of props, and I added those to the features as well.

Finally, each cartridge comes in different conditions. You could get one in perfect conditions, or one that's been used over and over. Don't worry, each cartridge has been tested and it's working properly anyways!!

This is just a simple game I made learning how to code for creative projects. It's also rumored that's a Golden Edition of this cartridge can be obtained somehow..

## Controls
- Move the player around using WASD or the arrow keys. Interact with stairs using SPACEBAR or E
- You can click the image to toggle sound on or off

## Credits
- I'm using p5js and I also tweaked to my needs a tutorial from Daniel Schiffman about raycasting
- The ambient music is from Joshua McLean, it's called Mountain Trials (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L_OYo2RS8iU&list=PLwJjxqYuirCLkq42mGw4XKGQlpZSfxsYd&index=8) and it's released under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license

metadata.name: Visa to the stars #211
metadata.description:
Generative space scenes with an illustrative look.

Use the capture functions to export in big after opening it in its own window, the artwork is full of details.

Press SPACE to show/hide the menu

Control the camera and explore the scene with :
- Mouse Left : Rotate
- Mouse Right : Pan
- Mouse Middle : Zoom

I wrote an article about the project, with a technical breakdown of the piece at https://ulucode.com/wp/visa-to-the-stars/


Decent GPU REQUIRED, you can tune the performances with the "Quality" setting in the menu.
Better performances with Chrome.

Keyboard shortcuts:
SPACE : show/hide menu
A : toggle anti-aliasing
C : take a capture of the ccurrently selected resolution
R : reset camera position/orientation
S : display stats
P : pause animation

metadata.name: Omega Point #55
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: Drifters #93
metadata.description:
In an undiscovered area, you've stumbled upon an unknown creature.
It looks weirdly haunting, and you're feeling a sense of unease.

You're wondering what it's doing.

It seems to move in patterns, and sometimes suddenly changes course.
Is it communicating?

(to whom?)

Setting aside your discomfort for a moment, you're realizing you could be seeing it wrong.
While the creature does look eerie and its motivations are unclear,
you realize every culture has its own appreciation of aesthetics,
and you can't help noticing there is a certain grace to this performance.

And it all makes sense.

You're witnessing uncharted explorations of elegance.

–

Append [?scale=<number>] to the url to scale the renderer.
Press [control / command + s] to save the current frame to a file.

© 2022 Monokai.

metadata.name: Proxima #265
metadata.description:
The preparations for the first mission began in 2142. It had become clear that mining petroleum on Earth would soon become financially unfeasible, so looking to other planets was the only logical choice. It took seventeen more years to perfect the technology so that the first colonists could reach Proxima b within the lifetime of one generation.

After 45 years of travelling at almost one-tenth of the speed of light, they reached their new home. It was rich in petrochemicals but scarce in the nutrients necessary for long term human survival. After merely six generations, humanity was forced to travel once again in search of a new world. The four missions that parted from the Proxima system to colonise other possibly habitable planets in the galaxy sparked a new age of human civilisation that would never see itself united and thriving again.

Eventually, all the colonies became independent societies as their differing interests drove them apart. Each small civilisation chose its path, wandering the void of space alone. Over time, millions of kilometres apart, each colony developed its own culture and traditions. While their habits and customs changed, some things remained the same across all the societies, like how it became a certain tradition to convert the outer world years and days to Earth time and celebrate holidays according to the calendar of the old world.

The new nomads learned from the first pilgrims. They used the technology once optimised for oil extraction to traverse other worlds, searching for sustenance. Peculiar wandering nonspaces emerged from the involuntary degrowth of human civilisation.

-----

Click on the image to open the menu. You may choose the quality from preview to the resolution of a print of approximately 30cm in height. In live mode, click on PNG to save the rendered image.
Depending on the device and CPU usage, it takes from a few seconds (on fast computers) to a minute (sometimes more) on mid-tier phones to render the image.

Requirements: 1GB of RAM. The system needs up to 200 MB of free RAM for rendering square preview images and up to 400 MB of free RAM for rendering square images at the highest resolution. We tested on Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge / Windows, Mac OS, Android, and iPhone, but please make sure it works on your device before minting.

Original piece by mrkswcz and Ismahelio. Made with Three.js. 

San Sebastian - Madrid. May 2022.

metadata.name: Bipole #54
metadata.description:
Two meandering paths are created with opposite flow vectors. The paths are drawn with a twisty drip brush.

Created for #tezos4tezos in May 2022.

Features 
- The amount each stroke's bristles twist as the path is drawn
- If each paths starts off strong or soft
- Splats at the starts and ends of the path
- Dark mode
- Monochrome or colored lines (colors from the p5riso palette)
- Paper fibers in the background
- 10% chance of dark orange and black lines

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 2400px by 1483px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.
